        <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
          <tr>
          <td align="left" valign="center">
          <font size="+1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#F52E00>
          <b>Features</b>
          </font>
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr><td colspan=2 height=1><img src=../../../img/blank.gif width=1 height=1></td></tr>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
        </table>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
The image below provides an overview of the features of the MicroCounter.
The device is powered by a single 1.5V AA-size battery, which should
last for 12 to 15 hours. At the left side (when viewed from the top)
is a three-position slide switch that is used to select the mode of operation.
It has an integrated push-button that allows selection of sub-modes.
Just below the mode switch is a 2 mm jack socket for connection of
an external antenna, which was available separately.
<br />
          <br />
          <table 
           border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%"><tr><td align="center" valign=top>
<a href="img/304410/003/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Click to see more">
<a href="img/304410/003/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Click to see more">
            <img src="img/mc_ext.png"
             style="
            "
             align="center"
             width="548px"
             vspace="4"
             alt="Click to see more"
             border=0
             />
            </div>
            </a>
            </td></tr><tr><td align=center>
          </td></tr></table>
<br />
At the top of the device is a 12-digit Liquid Crystal Display (<span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Liquid Crystal Display">LCD</span>)
that shows the current or re&#173;cor&#173;ded frequency. At the front are two push-buttons:
a grey one with a &uarr; symbol and an un&#173;mar&#173;ked black one. Both buttons
have the same function, which depends on the currently selected mode.
          </font>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <a name=mode></a>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
          <tr>
          <td align="left" valign="center">
          <font size="+0" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#F52E00>
          MODE selector
          </font>
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr><td colspan=2 height=1><img src=../../../img/blank.gif width=1 height=1></td></tr>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
        </table>
        <table border="0" width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td>
        <table width=100% cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td width=100%>
          <table
           class="table"
           width=100% border=0 cellspacing=1 cellpadding=2 bgcolor=#FFFFFF>
            <tr>
<td bgcolor="#E0E0E0" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555><b>Switch</font></td></b><td bgcolor="#E0E0E0" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555><b>Mode</font></td></b><td bgcolor="#E0E0E0" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555><b>Description</font></td></b>            </tr>
            <tr>
            <td bgcolor=#FFFFFF colspan=3><font size=-1>
            </font></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
<td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>Up</font></td><td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>NORMAL</font></td><td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>Shows running frequency for as long transmission continues.<br />Press &uarr; to alter gate time: 1 KHz, 100 Hz, 10 Hz.</font></td>            </tr>
            <tr>
<td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>&bullet; Press 1 &#215;</font></td><td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>FILTER</font></td><td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>Shows last detected frequency until new one is encountered.<br />Press &uarr; to alter gate time: 1 KHz, 100 Hz, 10 Hz.</font></td>            </tr>
            <tr>
<td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>&bullet; Press 2 &#215;</font></td><td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>CAPTURE</font></td><td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>Up to three frequencies are logged (until memory is full).<br />In this mode, only 1 kHz gate time is available.</font></td>            </tr>
            <tr>
<td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>Middle</font></td><td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>RECALL</font></td><td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>In this mode, previously recorded frequencies can be read.<br />Use &uarr; to scroll through captured frequencies.</font></td>            </tr>
            <tr>
<td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>Down</font></td><td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>OFF</font></td><td bgcolor="#F4F4F4" align="left" valign="top" style=" padding-left: 4px;"><font size=-1 size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>Device is off.</font></td>            </tr>
          </table>
<div style="height: 20px;"></div>        </td>
        </tr></table>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
          <tr>
          <td align="left" valign="center">
          <font size="+0" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#F52E00>
          Clear memory
          </font>
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr><td colspan=2 height=1><img src=../../../img/blank.gif width=1 height=1></td></tr>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
        </table>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
The device can capture up to three frequencies in its memory. When the
memory is full, a padlock pictogram is displayed on the <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Liquid Crystal Display">LCD</span> and no
further frequencies will be logged. To clear the three memory positions,
hold the &uarr; button while turning the device ON.
          </font>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <a name=int></a>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
<br />
<br />
          <br />
          <table 
           border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="100%"><tr><td align="center" valign=top>
<a href="img/304410/011/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Click to see more">
<a href="img/304410/011/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Click to see more">
            <img src="img/mc_int.png"
             style="
            "
             align="center"
             width="498px"
             vspace="4"
             alt="Click to see more"
             border=0
             />
            </div>
            </a>
            </td></tr><tr><td align=center>
          </td></tr></table>
          </font>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
          <tr>
          <td align="left" valign="center">
          <font size="+1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#F52E00>
          <b>Interior</b>
          </font>
          </td>
          </tr>
          <tr><td colspan=2 height=1><img src=../../../img/blank.gif width=1 height=1></td></tr>
          <tr><td height=4><img src="../../../img/blank.gif" width=1 height=4></td></tr>
        </table>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
The device is housed in a molded plastic case that consists of
two shells, held together by two Allen head screws at the rear.
The interior can be accessed by removing these two
screws, after which the rear case half can be removed.
This exposes the interior as shown in the image above.
          </font>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
Inside the device are two printed circuit boards (<span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Printed Circuit Board">PCB</span>s), interconnected
by an 8-pin header. The lower board (i.e. the larger one) is a universal
base board that holds the battery contacts, the <a href="#mode"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Jump to: MODE selector">MODE selector</span></a> and
the <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Liquid Crystal Display">LCD</span>. At the bottom side (shown on the right) is a <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Direct Current">DC</span>/<span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Direct Current">DC</span>
converter, a microcontroller, an <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Electrically Erasable Programmable Read-Only Memory" data-balloon-length="large">EEPROM</span> and a <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Liquid Crystal Display">LCD</span> driver.
<br />
<br />
The <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Direct Current">DC</span>/<span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Direct Current">DC</span> converter <a href="#data_1">[a]</a> is a Linear Technology LT1307, which
converts the 1.5V battery voltage to 3.3V for the digital circuits.
The 8-bit micro&#173;con&#173;trol&#173;ler <a href="#data_2">[b]</a> is a COP8SAC720M9 with 4KB <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="One-Time Programmable (PROM)">OTP</span>,
128 bytes of <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Random Access Memory">RAM</span> and a Microwire <sup><font color="#FF8800">1</font></sup> interface.
          </font></td>
          <td>&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
          <td align=center valign=top width=100>
          <table 
           border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" ><tr><td align="center" valign=top>
<a href="img/304410/016/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Base board - bottom view">
<a href="img/304410/016/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Base board - bottom view">
            <img src="img/304410/016/small.jpg"
             style="
             max-width: 618px;
            "
             align="left"
             vspace="4"
             alt="Base board - bottom view"
             border=0
             width=298 height=200
             />
            </div>
            </a>
            </td></tr><tr><td align=center>
          </td></tr></table>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
Note that this is a universal board  that was also used in the other
devices of the <a href="#fam"><span data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Jump to: Techtoyz family">Techtoyz family</span></a> (<span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Radio Frequency">RF</span> detector & <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Double-Tone Multi-Frequency">DTMF</span> decoder),
albeit with different firmware.
The data bus of the microcontroller is connected a Philips PCF8576CT universal <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Liquid Crystal Display">LCD</span>
driver <a href="#data_3">[c]</a> that drives the Motorola pager display.
          </font>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
The I<sup>2</sup>C bus of the microcontroller is connected to a Catalyst Semiconductor <sup><font color="#FF8800">2</font></sup>
128-byte 24C01 <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Electrically Erasable Programmable Read-Only Memory" data-balloon-length="large">EEPROM</span> <a href="#data_4">[d]</a> for storing the captured frequencies.
<br />
<br />
A separate <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Serial Peripheral Interface">SPI</span> bus is brought out to the 8-pin expansion con&#173;nec&#173;tor on which the
<i>feature board</i> is fitted. This board &mdash; shown in the image on the right &mdash;
is specific for the MicroCounter and is built around a Xilinx CX3430
Spartan 3 Field-Programmable Gate Array (<span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Field Programmable Gate Array">FPGA</span>) <a href="#data_5">[e]</a>.
The anten&#173;na signal is first amplified in a two-stage ampli&#173;fier with BFR505
wideband transistors (N30)  <a href="#data_6">[f]</a> and then passed to an UPB587 prescaler <a href="#data_7">[g]</a>.
          </font></td>
          <td>&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
          <td align=center valign=top width=100>
          <table 
           border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" ><tr><td align="center" valign=top>
<a href="img/304410/018/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Feature board - bottom view">
<a href="img/304410/018/full.jpg">            <div style="position: relative;" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Feature board - bottom view">
            <img src="img/304410/018/small.jpg"
             style="
             max-width: 618px;
            "
             align="left"
             vspace="4"
             alt="Feature board - bottom view"
             border=0
             width=298 height=200
             />
            </div>
            </a>
            </td></tr><tr><td align=center>
          </td></tr></table>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr>
          <td valign=top align=left>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#555555>
The prescaler divides the frequency by eight before applying the signal to the
<span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Field Programmable Gate Array">FPGA</span>, where it is further processed. The <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Field Programmable Gate Array">FPGA</span> effectively implements the
complete frequency counter in firmware. When the device is switch ON, it displays
the text 'OPTO' whilst the firmware
is transferred via the <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Serial Peripheral Interface">SPI</span> interface from the microcontroller on the base board
to the <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Field Programmable Gate Array">FPGA</span> on the feature board.
          </font>
          </td></tr>
        </table>
<br />        <table width="50" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr>
        <td style="border-top: 1px solid #aaa;"><img src="../img/blank.gif" width="1" height="5"/></td>
        </tr></table>
        <table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0>
          <tr><td>
          <font size="-1" face="Lucida Grande,Arial,Verdana,sans-serif" color=#888888><small>
          <ol>
          <li>
Microwire is the National Semiconductor variant of the Philips I<sup>2</sup>C standard.
          </li>
          <li>
Catalyst Semiconductor, Inc. (CSI) is the original inventor and patent holder
  of the <span class="short tooltip-red" data-balloon-pos="up" aria-label="Electrically Erasable Programmable Read-Only Memory" data-balloon-length="large">EEPROM</span>.
          </ol>
          </small></font></td></tr>
        </table>
